Every day, we are bombarded with messages about the importance of being healthy. We are told to eat right, exercise, and get enough sleep. But what does it really mean to be healthy? And how can we achieve it?

There are many different ways to define health. The World Health Organization defines it as “a state of complete physical, mental, and social well-being and not merely the absence of disease or infirmity.” This definition emphasizes the importance of not only physical health, but also mental and social well-being.

One way to achieve good health is through a balanced diet. Eating a variety of foods from all the food groups can help ensure that we get the nutrients we need to stay healthy. This includes fruits and vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. It’s also important to limit our intake of processed foods, sugary drinks, and unhealthy fats.

Exercise is another important component of a healthy lifestyle. Regular physical activity can help reduce the risk of chronic diseases such as heart disease, diabetes, and obesity. It can also improve mental health by reducing stress and anxiety. The American Heart Association recommends at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic activity or 75 minutes of vigorous-intensity aerobic activity per week, along with muscle-strengthening activities at least two days per week.

Getting enough sleep is also crucial for good health. Adults should aim for 7-9 hours of sleep per night. Lack of sleep can lead to a weakened immune system, weight gain, and an increased risk of chronic diseases. It can also affect our mood and cognitive function.

In addition to these physical aspects of health, it’s also important to take care of our mental and emotional well-being. This can include practicing mindfulness and meditation, seeking therapy or counseling when needed, and finding healthy ways to cope with stress.

Overall, being healthy is about taking care of our bodies and minds, and making choices that support our overall well-being. It’s not always easy, but the benefits of a healthy lifestyle are well worth the effort.

About 15 million people in the U.S. have reportedly used dating sites or apps to find romance, and the numbers are growing as more mainstream platforms adapt to meet the needs of a more mature audience.

For instance, the dating app Tinder has gained a reputation as a hookup app, but the vast majority of its users (80%) say they want to find a meaningful relationship on the platform, according to a survey by the University of Texas.



As of 2019, Tinder had over 4.1 million paid subscribers, and it saw over 2 billion views per day. That’s a lot of swiping.

That’s why senior dating sites like 50plus-Club have become particularly popular among single men and women in their 50s, 60s, 70s, and up. These platforms give people a user-friendly interface, proactive safety features, and a targeted senior audience to meet.

50plus-Club is a pioneer in this niche dating market. The dating site caters exclusively to the over-50 crowd, and it has seen great success as a brand.

“We are more than a dating site,” said 50plus-Club Co-Founder Marianna Exter. “We are a community for baby boomers and seniors.”

Seniors Go Online to Make New Friends & Find Relationships

Sven and Marianna Exter owned and operated a dating site for German singles of all ages. They took pride in giving people an opportunity to meet the love of their life, and they keenly monitored activity on the platform.

As time went by, Sven and Marianna noticed that the majority of members over 50 were more serious about searching for a date. These members searched more proactively than any other age group, and they were more likely to pursue offline relationships.

Marianna Exter and her husband run 50plus-Club as a resource for seniors in the dating scene.

However, many general dating sites and apps turn dating into a game where singles swipe and match in an endless carousel. Such platforms may appeal to young casual daters, but they often don’t suit the needs of the older dating population. That’s why Marianna and Sven decided to break new ground and create a dating site where singles over 50 could take their time and form real relationships.

In 2005, the couple launched 50plus-Club.com as one of the first senior dating sites for singles in Germany, Austria, and Switzerland. Three years later, the site expanded into the U.S., Canada, the U.K., and Ireland, and today it’s up and running in 10 countries. The dating site caters exclusively to the over-50 crowd, and it has seen great success as a brand.

“We realized that this age group was clearly lacking the access to places and the opportunity to meet new people,” Marianna said. “That’s, it’s our mission to help everyone over 50 find the love of their life.”

The 50plus-Club team consistently puts the needs of users first and develops easy-to-understand features to help them get where they want to go online. The dating site offers multiple ways to connect and discover commonality, and it has led to thousands of success stories in the last few years. Whether you’re looking for a pen pal, a friend, or a relationship, 50plus-Club can help you find your perfect match.

A Forum for Friendship & Support

Up until now, 50plus-Club has attracted over 600,000 singles over 45 and helped them find friendship and love online. The site is designed to help men and women of a certain age find one another, but it’s also intended to help singles learn more about themselves, find suitable companions for activities, and enjoy life to the fullest.

The site’s features foster a friendly space for singles to engage with one another. Members can meet other people who share similar values and interests by browsing member profiles, sending private messages, or joining the public forums.

“The 50plus-Club forum is the place for seniors and everyone over 50,” Marianna said. “Whether you are looking for a serious relationship or just some interesting, new friends, in our community you will find what you are looking for.”

The Los Angeles County Department of Public Health (DPH) is hosting a community meeting to discuss the Exide Residential Cleanup Plan and the Draft Environmental Impact Report (DEIR). The meeting will be held on Saturday, February 18, 2017 from 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM at the Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority (Metro) Board Room, located at 1 Gateway Plaza, Los Angeles, CA 90012.

The meeting will provide an opportunity for community members to learn more about the cleanup plan and DEIR, ask questions, and provide feedback. DPH staff will be available to answer questions and provide information about the cleanup process.

The Exide Residential Cleanup Plan is a comprehensive plan to address the contamination caused by the Exide Technologies battery recycling facility in Vernon, CA. The plan includes the removal of contaminated soil from residential properties, the installation of air monitoring equipment, and the implementation of health and safety measures to protect the community.

The DEIR is a document that evaluates the potential environmental impacts of the cleanup plan and identifies measures to mitigate those impacts. The DEIR is available for public review and comment until March 31, 2017.

The Los Angeles Regional Water Quality Control Board (LARWQCB) will hold a public hearing to consider adoption of a resolution to approve an amendment to the Water Quality Control Plan for the Los Angeles Region (Basin Plan) to incorporate a Total Maximum Daily Load (TMDL) for bacteria in the Los Angeles River and its tributaries.

The proposed Basin Plan amendment will establish TMDLs for bacteria in the Los Angeles River and its tributaries to protect water contact recreation (REC-1) beneficial uses by reducing fecal indicator bacteria levels during wet and dry weather. The proposed TMDLs include numeric targets, source analysis, allocations, and a compliance schedule. The proposed TMDLs also include an implementation plan that identifies the actions necessary to achieve the TMDLs, including monitoring and special studies, and a framework for adaptive management.

The proposed Basin Plan amendment and associated documents are available at the LARWQCB website.

The public comment period for the proposed Basin Plan amendment is from May 5, 2017 to June 19, 2017. Written comments must be received by 5:00 PM on June 19, 2017 and should be submitted to:

Los Angeles Regional Water Quality Control Board

Attn: Annelisa Moe

320 West 4th Street, Suite 200

Los Angeles, CA 90013

Comments may also be submitted via email to Annelisa.Moe@Waterboards.ca.gov.

The LARWQCB will also hold a public workshop on the proposed Basin Plan amendment on May 25, 2017, 10:00 AM – 12:00 PM at the LARWQCB office.

For more information, please contact Annelisa Moe at Annelisa.Moe@Waterboards.ca.gov or (213) 576-6782.

The State Water Resources Control Board (State Water Board) will hold a public workshop to receive information and solicit public input on the proposed framework for the regulation of direct potable reuse in California.

The workshop will be held on Tuesday, May 30, 2017, 9:30 AM – 12:30 PM in the Coastal Hearing Room at the Joe Serna Jr. – CalEPA Headquarters Building, 1001 I Street, Second Floor, Sacramento, CA 95814.

The State Water Board is developing uniform water recycling criteria for direct potable reuse in accordance with Water Code section 13561. The proposed framework describes the State Water Board’s approach to developing the criteria and key issues that will be addressed. The State Water Board will consider the information presented, as well as all oral and written comments received, in developing the uniform water recycling criteria for direct potable reuse.

The Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority (Metro) invites you to attend a community meeting to learn about the proposed Eastside Transit Corridor Phase 2 Project. The project is currently in the Draft Environmental Impact Statement/Environmental Impact Report (Draft EIS/EIR) phase, which evaluates the potential environmental impacts and benefits of the project alternatives.

The project proposes to extend the Metro Gold Line further east from its current terminus at Atlantic Station in East Los Angeles. Two build alternatives are being studied: SR-60 LRT and Washington Boulevard LRT. The SR-60 LRT alternative would extend the Metro Gold Line 6.9 miles to South El Monte. The Washington Boulevard LRT alternative would extend the Metro Gold Line 9.5 miles to Whittier.

The purpose of the meeting is to provide an update on the project and to seek input on the Draft EIS/EIR. The meeting will include a presentation followed by a question and answer session.

The meeting will be held on Saturday, February 11, 2017, from 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM at the Metro Headquarters Building, One Gateway Plaza, Los Angeles, CA 90012.

For more information, please visit the project website at www.metro.net/eastsidephase2 or contact the project hotline at (213) 922-3012.

We look forward to seeing you at the meeting!

Sincerely,

The Metro Eastside Transit Corridor Phase 2 Project Team

A German Couple Started 50plus-Club as a Retirement Business

The story of 50plus-Club began in 2005 in Munich, Germany. Sven and Marianna Exter owned and operated a dating site for German singles of all ages. They took pride in giving people an opportunity to meet the love of their life, and they keenly monitored activity on the platform.

As time went by, Sven and Marianna noticed that the majority of members over 50 were more serious about searching for a date. These members searched more proactively than any other age group, and they were more likely to pursue offline relationships.

Marianna Exter and her husband run 50plus-Club as a resource for seniors in the dating scene.

The following is a list of the most common internal and external parasites that can affect your dog. The list is not all inclusive, but it does cover the most common parasites that can affect your dog.

Internal Parasites

Roundworms

Roundworms are the most common internal parasite in dogs. They are long, white, and spaghetti-like in appearance. They can be found in the small intestine and can grow up to 7 inches long. Roundworms can be passed from mother to puppy through the placenta or through the milk. They can also be passed through the feces of an infected dog. Roundworms can cause vomiting, diarrhea, weight loss, and a pot-bellied appearance.

Hookworms

Hookworms are small, thin worms that attach themselves to the lining of the small intestine. They can cause anemia, weight loss, and diarrhea. Hookworms can be passed from mother to puppy through the placenta or through the milk. They can also be passed through the feces of an infected dog.

Whipworms

Whipworms are long, thin worms that live in the large intestine. They can cause diarrhea, weight loss, and anemia. Whipworms can be passed through the feces of an infected dog.

Tapeworms

Tapeworms are long, flat worms that live in the small intestine. They can cause weight loss, diarrhea, and vomiting. Tapeworms can be passed through the feces of an infected dog or through the ingestion of fleas.

Heartworms

Heartworms are long, thin worms that live in the heart and lungs of dogs. They are transmitted through the bite of an infected mosquito. Heartworms can cause coughing, difficulty breathing, weight loss, and heart failure.

External Parasites

Fleas

Fleas are small, wingless insects that feed on the blood of dogs. They can cause itching, hair loss, and skin infections. Fleas can also transmit tapeworms and other diseases.

Ticks

Ticks are small, blood-sucking arachnids that can transmit diseases such as Lyme disease, Rocky Mountain spotted fever, and ehrlichiosis. They can also cause anemia and skin irritation.

Mites

Mites are tiny arachnids that can cause skin irritation, hair loss, and ear infections. There are several different types of mites that can affect dogs, including ear mites, mange mites, and demodex mites.

Lice

Lice are small, wingless insects that feed on the skin and hair of dogs. They can cause itching, hair loss, and skin infections.

Prevention and Treatment

Preventing and treating parasites in dogs is important for their health and well-being. Regular veterinary check-ups, fecal exams, and heartworm testing can help detect parasites early. There are also several medications available to prevent and treat internal and external parasites in dogs. It is important to follow your veterinarian’s recommendations for parasite prevention and treatment to keep your dog healthy and happy.
